comments.content: In the light, stromal ADP levels decrease due to photophosphorylation, this favors PPDK-regulatory protein-catalyzed dephosphorylation (of PPDK) reaction resulting in activation of PPDK.
In the dark, stromal ADP levels increaseand this favors PPDK-regulatory protein-catalyzed phosphorylation (of PPDK) reaction resulting in inactive form of PPDK.
Active PPDK found in light conditions has a phosphorylated Histitine and a hydroxy Threonine residue.

This non enzymatic step of the pathway involves carbomylation of the important lysinne residue by the CO2, followed by Mg2+ ion binding. The resulting formation of complex Rubisco-CO2-Mg contributes to the active form of Rubisco, to carry out its carboxylase activity.
Inactive PPDK found in dark conditions has a phosphorylated Histitine and a phosphorylated threonine residue.

Rubisco activase catalyzes the ATP dependent release of D-ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate present in the active site of Rubisco. IN th eprocess it exposes the important Lysince residue for the next stem in carbomylation of Rubisco.

comments.content: C4 carbon fixation is the CO2 fixation mechanism used by the maize plant which harbors a kranz anatomy in its leaves. In maize it is carried out in two types of cells namely the mesophyll cell where Carbonic anhydrase fixes diffused CO2 to HCO3 and the enzyme PEP carboxylase converts HCO3 into oxaloacetic acid. Malate dehydrogenase catalyzes the conversion of oxaloacetic acid into malate in the mesophyll chloroplast. Malate is transported to the bundle sheath cell cytoplasm followed by the bundle sheath chloroplast where it is broken down into pyruvate and the CO2. This CO2 molecule is now fixed into 3-phosphoglycerate molecule by the active Rubisco enzyme. This process is different from the C3-carbon assimilation in rice which occurs only in the bundle sheath cells.
